<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>In a statement to the Daily Sun, SAMA organisers have said that the increase in entries is a vote of confidence in the integrity and prestige of the SAMA as the ultimate music honour for local and continental musicians.“We are thankful that year after year, the industry gives us a thumbs up knowing that this is a platform that celebrates worthy talent.  As we head into the 24th edition of the SAMA we are confident of our credibility and take pride in our longstanding track record that speaks for itself,” said the CEO of the Recording Industry of South Africa (RiSA), Nhlanhla Sibisi.The most popular category by far is the Best Music Video of the Year category, with 127 entries.This narrowly beats out the Best Collaboration category, which attracted some 100 submissions.The Best Produced Album stands at 86 entrants, while Best Dance Album boasts 53.Other competitive categories are Best Engineered Album with 42 entries, and the Best Hip Hop Album stands at 26 entries. There has been an uptake of jazz with an impressive 25 entries, while Best Kwaito Album has garnered 8. The Best Contemporary Faith Music Album category will be a battleground for the 30 entrants and the Best African Adult Contemporary Album category will see some 21 of the best battling it out for a nod.The Best Traditional Faith Music Album is also sitting at 21 and the rhythms of Maskandi ring in 16.The Best African Artist Album category has seen an incredible jump last year’s from 6 to an impressive 30.Additionally, in an effort to achieve complete transparency, the SAMAs have, for the second year in a row, the released the complete list of entries to the public.“We are still committed to the practice of openness and transparency and a fair selection process. We release these entries for the industry and music supporters to be kept abreast of the developments as we progress through the stages of the SAMA. We also do so to avoid any surprises when we announce the final nomination list in the next few weeks," sad Nhlanhla.In order to qualify for entry, recording companies and other interested parties go through a stringent vetting process presided over by RiSA officials and record company representatives that have ensured that the entries meet all the eligibility requirements.Those who ticked all the boxes have now been handed over to a panel of independent judges drawn from radio, television, newspapers, blogs and the recording industry for judging.The SAMA office will then release only five nominees in each category as voted for by the panels and verified by an independent audit firm.